steps {
  type: CORTEX_STEP_TYPE_USER_INPUT
  status: CORTEX_STEP_STATUS_DONE
  metadata {
    created_at {
      seconds: 1779640257
      nanos: 553185376
    }
    source: CORTEX_STEP_SOURCE_USER_EXPLICIT
  }
  user_input {
    user_response: "You are an expert Frontend Engineer and Geospatial Data Specialist. Build a high-performance, responsive single-page React application (using Vite, Tailwind CSS, and TypeScript) that calculates and visualizes real-time 3D building shadows on a city map grid to help users find sunlight for outdoor dining, hanging out, and photography.\n\n### Technical Stack Constraints:\n1. Map Engine: Use MapLibre GL JS (open-source) for the base map, combined with Deck.gl for the 3D rendering layer.\n2. Shadow Engine: Implement Deck.gl\'s native `SunLight` / Effects system to handle client-side, WebGL-accelerated 3D building shadow casting.\n3. Solar Calculations: Use the `suncalc` npm package to determine precise sun position based on latitude, longitude, date, and time.\n4. Performance: No server-side shadow computations. All shadow geometry projections must be rendered via the client-side GPU to ensure smooth, \"snappy\" 60FPS timeline scrubbing.\n\n### Core Features to Implement:\n1. 3D Map Grid: Render 3D extruded building structures using open-source OpenStreetMap (OSM) vector tile data. \n2. Interactive Time Slider: A smooth UI timeline controller allowing users to select any date and scrub through 24 hours of the day, updating the map\'s shadows instantly in real time.\n3. Photographer Dashboard: A persistent UI panel displaying:\n   - Golden Hour & Blue Hour windows (calculated via suncalc)\n   - Current Solar Azimuth and Elevation degrees\n   - A toggle to automatically snap the timeline directly to the upcoming Golden Hour.\n4. UI Overlay: Clean, minimalist overlay containing a search/geocoding bar for city selection, a calendar date-picker, and a \"Find Sun\" toggle that highlights unshaded coordinates on the map floor.\n\nProvide a complete, modular folder structure and the primary file implementations (`App.tsx`, `MapContainer.tsx`, `ControlPanel.tsx`) using clean, well-documented code."
    items {
      text: "You are an expert Frontend Engineer and Geospatial Data Specialist. Build a high-performance, responsive single-page React application (using Vite, Tailwind CSS, and TypeScript) that calculates and visualizes real-time 3D building shadows on a city map grid to help users find sunlight for outdoor dining, hanging out, and photography.\n\n### Technical Stack Constraints:\n1. Map Engine: Use MapLibre GL JS (open-source) for the base map, combined with Deck.gl for the 3D rendering layer.\n2. Shadow Engine: Implement Deck.gl\'s native `SunLight` / Effects system to handle client-side, WebGL-accelerated 3D building shadow casting.\n3. Solar Calculations: Use the `suncalc` npm package to determine precise sun position based on latitude, longitude, date, and time.\n4. Performance: No server-side shadow computations. All shadow geometry projections must be rendered via the client-side GPU to ensure smooth, \"snappy\" 60FPS timeline scrubbing.\n\n### Core Features to Implement:\n1. 3D Map Grid: Render 3D extruded building structures using open-source OpenStreetMap (OSM) vector tile data. \n2. Interactive Time Slider: A smooth UI timeline controller allowing users to select any date and scrub through 24 hours of the day, updating the map\'s shadows instantly in real time.\n3. Photographer Dashboard: A persistent UI panel displaying:\n   - Golden Hour & Blue Hour windows (calculated via suncalc)\n   - Current Solar Azimuth and Elevation degrees\n   - A toggle to automatically snap the timeline directly to the upcoming Golden Hour.\n4. UI Overlay: Clean, minimalist overlay containing a search/geocoding bar for city selection, a calendar date-picker, and a \"Find Sun\" toggle that highlights unshaded coordinates on the map floor.\n\nProvide a complete, modular folder structure and the primary file implementations (`App.tsx`, `MapContainer.tsx`, `ControlPanel.tsx`) using clean, well-documented code."
    }
  }
}
