  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Clarifying Module Imports**\n\nI\'ve clarified the import process for `react-map-gl`, recognizing the standard `import Map from \'react-map-gl\'` approach. Also, I\'ve noted the specific import for MapLibre: `import Map from \'react-map-gl/maplibre\'`. Next, I will shift focus towards the requirements for 3D buildings.\n\n\n**Investigating Basemap Options**\n\nI\'m now investigating basemap options for rendering 3D buildings. I\'m looking into whether Mapbox or MapLibre offers free vector tiles, and if not, exploring alternatives like Carto or OpenMapTiles (if configured). I\'m also considering Protomaps\' free public endpoint and realizing we *might* bypass the need for a vector tile service for the basemap altogether if we use DeckGL to render OSM building GeoJSON. My focus is on determining available vector tile servers, such as the CyberJapanData example, and on whether `react-map-gl` can render vector tiles.\n\n\n**Evaluating Vector Tile Sources**\n\nI\'m now deep-diving into vector tile sources for 3D buildings and basemaps. I\'ve ruled out Carto for 3D buildings and am looking at options, weighing Microsoft Building Footprints (slow Overpass) against the Overture Maps parquet data (too complex). I\'ve decided to use a raster base map from `tile.openstreetmap.org` along with a vector tile source for buildings, perhaps Nextzen (API key needed), or a Mapbox GL style alternative, but this leads to 2D. I\'m also exploring `osmbuildings.org` and Tilezen with DeckGL\'s `MVTLayer`, using Carto or osmbuildings.\n\n\n**Analyzing OSM Buildings Data**\n\nI\'m now investigating OSM Buildings data and discovered their URL returns GeoJSON vector tiles. I\'m leaning toward using `GeoJsonLayer` or `TileLayer` for rendering. However, I\'m now thinking `MVTLayer` might be a better fit if an MVT source exists. I\'ve confirmed an OSM Buildings URL works, now considering using CARTO positron basemap. I\'m exploring adding an `MVTLayer` for buildings and wondering if CARTO provides buildings in MVT format. The Positron style appears to include building footprints in its vector tiles.\n\n\n**Confirming Shadow Casting**\n\nI\'ve confirmed that the `positron-gl-style` contains building layers. The `react-map-gl` can\'t natively extrude buildings, but it\'s more like `react-map-gl` will *use* `deck.gl` to render things like buildings in an extruded way, or as MVT layers. Client-side shadow casting requires DeckGL layers, such as `MVTLayer` or `GeoJsonLayer`, using `extruded: true` with `getElevation` and *not* the base map. Now I\'m checking for an MVT tile server with building heights, like Mapzen or Nextzen, where `height` or `render_height` can be found in the `building` layer.\n\n\n**Considering API Key Alternatives**\n\nI\'m now considering workarounds due to the API key limitation. I\'ve realized Carto\'s public dataset of building footprints could be useful. I\'m exploring the `positron-gl-style` to determine if it contains height data in the building layers. A static GeoJSON for a specific city like Manhattan is tempting, but the need for global coverage favors Mapbox with a user-provided token. I\'ll include guidance for that.\n\n\n**Evaluating Overpass API**\n\nI\'m now shifting gears, and I\'ve decided to explore using the standard OSM Overpass API to fetch building footprints dynamically based on the current viewport. I\'m focusing on crafting a viewport-based Overpass query to retrieve building data, including `height` or `building:levels`. Although the plan seemed viable at first, I\'ve realized fetching building data directly might introduce latency issues and could overload Overpass if zooming a lot. I\'m now exploring `TileLayer` with OSMBuildings as an alternative.\n\n```text\n```\n\n\n"
    thinking_duration {
      seconds: 21
      nanos: 9869963
    }
    stop_reason: STOP_REASON_CLIENT_TOOL_PARSE_ERROR
  }
}
