    thinking: "**Considering Initial Load**\n\nI\'ve been examining the app\'s startup sequence, specifically the initial coordinates in `App.tsx` and the subsequent `fetchBuildingsFn` call. The Overpass API delay, around a second or two, is quite noticeable. I\'m brainstorming options for a more engaging initial display during this loading period.\n\n\n**Adding Photographer Features**\n\nI\'ve incorporated the features for the Photographer Dashboard into `ControlPanel.tsx`. This includes Golden Hour and Blue Hour windows, solar azimuth/elevation, and an automatic timeline snap to Golden Hour toggle. I\'m now verifying the unshaded area highlighting, specifically whether `findSunActive` is being used correctly in `MapContainer.tsx` in relation to the new `SunLight` implementation. I\'m testing the effect of the sunlight implementation to ensure shadow casting is occurring on a base floor layer.\n\n\n**Fixing Shadow Visibility**\n\nI\'ve realized the ground layer\'s transparency was preventing shadows from being visible on the MapLibre base map. DeckGL shadows only render on DeckGL layers. The current implementation renders shadows on the transparent ground layer, so they\'re invisible. I\'m exploring solutions. A constant, low-opacity color for the ground is needed to receive the shadows. The trick involves the base map!\n\n\n**Exploring Shadow Interactions**\n\nI\'m now focusing on shadow visibility on the ground layer. My initial ideas of transparent polygons and low-opacity colors didn\'t pan out. I experimented with different blend modes and finally have something that looks promising. A white polygon with `operation: \'multiply\'` appears to darken the basemap only where shadows are cast, but I need to investigate if the shadow map is blocked by the buildings.\n\n\n**Analyzing Shadow Implementation**\n\nI\'ve been thinking about getting DeckGL shadows to function correctly with the underlying MapLibre base map. I\'ve realized standard WebGL blending won\'t work between separate canvases. My focus has shifted to the necessity of drawing the ground within DeckGL to ensure shadow visibility. This would necessarily occlude the Mapbox base map. I\'m starting to consider the approach of tinted ground polygons with a slightly dark tone, rather than trying to blend shadows onto the MapLibre map directly.\n\n\n**Refining Shadow Visibility**\n\nI\'ve been reconsidering the ground layer\'s color and opacity to improve shadow visibility. My previous idea of using black fill wasn\'t effective due to how the lighting calculations work in DeckGL. I\'m now testing a semi-transparent gray: `[255, 255, 255, 30]`. This should create a subtle white overlay that darkens when in shadow, which, in turn, allows for shadows to be visible on the map. I\'m verifying how this functions with the existing `findSunActive` toggle.\n\n\n"
    thinking_duration {
      seconds: 17
      nanos: 470996251
    }
    stop_reason: STOP_REASON_STOP_PATTERN
  }
}
